<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ870331-0037 </DOCNO><HL> What's News --Business and Finance</HL><DD> 03/31/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><TEXT>   THE DOLLAR FELL FURTHER despite continued intervention, triggering a huge sell-off in securities markets around the world. Stock and bond prices skidded in New York as the Dow Jones industrials plunged 57.39 points, the third biggest point drop ever, to 2278.41. The fall followed similar routs in London and Tokyo.    ---   Harper andamp; Row agreed to be acquired by Rupert Murdoch's News Corp. for $65 a share, or $300 million. The surprise accord, which appeared to end a three-week bidding war, will make Murdoch a major player in the book publishing industry.    ---   New-home sales fell 2.7% in February following a revised 8.6% drop in January. But economists expect continued low mortgage rates to spur sales in the months ahead. Several said the recent drops may reflect a shift by buyers to existing homes.    ---   RJR Nabisco announced that a possible spinoff of its tobacco business into a master limited partnership is unlikely anytime soon.    ---   Japan turned down a U.S. demand that Tokyo allow significant foreign participation in a proposed global telecommunications venture. But U.S. officials believe that the Japanese decision can be reversed.    ---   The SEC was barred from sharing evidence with the U.S. Attorney's office in New York in an insider-trading case. Lawyers disagreed over the impact of the ruling but said it could hurt the U.S. Attorney's office.    ---   Carl Icahn's meetings with Ivan Boesky and Gulf andamp; Western's chairman in 1985 are being examined as part of an SEC inquiry, sources said. Investigators are trying to see if Icahn and Boesky tried to pressure Gulf andamp; Western into a buyout.    ---   Four accounting firms sued the American Institute of CPAs to prevent it from requiring some members to join a self-regulatory group. The suit was said to reflect a growing rift between big and small CPA firms.    ---   Penn Central Corp. named Chairman Carl Lindner to the added post of chief executive. The company also is considering spinning off all or part of its electronic parts business.    ---   Financier Marvin Warner drew a 3 1/2-year prison term and was ordered to pay $22 million in restitution in the 1985 collapse of Home State Savings.    ---   Allegheny International sold its Britain-based Wilkinson Sword group to Swedish Match Co. for $160 million. It is Allegheny's biggest divestiture since it began scaling back and focusing on North American operations.    ---   PaineWebber was sued by five former top brokers who claim the securities firm hired them only to obtain their clients. The former brokers, who said they were subsequently fired, are seeking $15 million in damages.    ---   Markets --   Stocks: Volume 208,440,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials 2278.41, off 57.39; transportation 915.21, off 20.23; utilities 212.17, off 4.90.    Bonds: Shearson Lehman Treasury bonds 1384.04, off 25.54.    Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 115.42, off 0.14; spot index 116.08, up 0.04.    Dollar: 146.25 yen, off 0.85; 1.7995 marks, off 0.0168. </TEXT></DOC>